AGI - Red Cross officials are in Rafah, in the south of the Gaza Strip, for the release of a first group of hostages by the Islamist terrorist group Hamas The Israeli media report it, citing a source of security. According to Al Jazeera, Tal Shoham and Avera Mengistu will be released in Rafah, while the other four, Omer Shem-Tov, Eliya Cohen, Omer Wenkert and Hisham al-Sayed, will be delivered later in the Nuseirat refugee camp, in the central area of the Strip. Al Jazeera's images show that both locations were set up for hostage delivery. The crowd is reaching the two sites.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Fighters of the Qassam Brigades, the military wing of Hamas, were deployed in the places where the delivery of six Israeli prisoners takes place. The scenes on site recall previous deliveries, with rows of armed Hamas fighters who guard, while the stage at Rafah was set up with banners, one of which says "We are the extreme force". &nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Rafah came the first group of kidnapped. A &nbsp; Red Cross representative spoke with each of them, while a second official signed on stage the delivery documents. To be released, as said, are&nbsp;Avera Mengistu and Tal Shoham. The 37-year-old of Ethiopian origins and the 39-year-old Austrian-Israeli were shown to the crowd on stage by the militiamen of Hamas during the usual release ceremony. Shoham was kidnapped by his wife's parents' house Adi in Kibbutz Bèeri on October 7, 2023. In the massacre were murdered the father and uncle of the woman, while she and their two young children, Naveh and Yahel, were taken hostage and released during the short break in November 2023. Mengistu, suffering from mental problems, had entered his spontaneous will in Gaza in 2014, crossing the border near Zikim Beach, just north of the Strip. He remained a prisoner for over 10 years.&nbsp;
Tal Shoham was transported with Israeli Air Force helicopter from a military base near the Gaza border to a hospital in the center of Israel where he will receive medical care and meet the rest of his family brought with another helicopter. Also Avera Mengistu, who spent after 3,821 days in the hands of Hamas, met the members of his family at the IDF base before being taken to the hospital by helicopter.&nbsp;
The Red Cross then headed towards the second issue of the hostages in Nuseirat, in the middle of the Strip: Omer Shem-Tov, Eliya Cohen, Omer Wenkert and Hisham al-Sayed.&nbsp;Hamas announced that the latter hostage, an Israeli Bedouin held prisoner in Gaza since 2015, will be released without a public ceremony, respectful for his family. Al-Sayed, suffering from mental problems according to his family, was captured after voluntarily crossing the border with the Strip almost a decade ago. The 37-year-old will be delivered to the Red Cross later.
&nbsp;

