AGI - The fate of the Bibas shakes Israel, outraged both for the failure to return the body of the mother Shiri, exchanged in the coffin with a Palestinian woman with an unknown identity, and for the cruel death that would be inflicted on the two children. Kfir and Ariel, the two red-haired brethren seized when they were only 10 months and 4 years old and returned yesterday from Hamas in a coffin, were killed not with a gunshot but bare hands.
&nbsp;
"Unlike the lies of Hamas, Ariel and Kfir were not killed in an air strike, they were murdered in cold blood by the terrorists," said the spokesman of the Idf, Dianel Hagari, stating that "the terrorists did not shoot the two children, killed them with bare hands. They then committed horrible acts to cover these atrocities." Affirmations, he added, which are based on "both forensic results, the identification process, and the intelligence that supports these results".
<div </div
"A barbaric act that undeniably bears witness to the brutality" of their kidnappers, underlined the Family Forum of the hostages, appealing to "act, the fight to bring everyone home must not stop for a moment." On social media it made itself feel Ofri Bibas, the aunt of Ariel and Kfir: "I'm sorry, you didn't deserve any of this. We will miss you forever, and we will not give up Mom Shiri," he said, reasserting that the family "does not ask for revenge now, asks Shiri," which must be returned immediately, along with all the other hostages, alive and dead.
&nbsp;
The Bibas also pointed the finger against Benjamin Netanyahu, accusing him of "abandoned" their loved ones on October 7 and during the captivity. The brother of Ofri and father of children, Yarden, taken away on October 7 separately from the family, was released at the beginning of the month after 484 days of imprisonment. To him "they are turned our hearts", said Hagari, ensuring that "everything possible to bring Shiri home and all the other 69 hostages still held in horrible and brutal conditions from Hamas to Gaza".
&nbsp;
Premier Benjamin Netanyahu has arrived the harsh condemnation for the failure to return the body of the young mother, a " cruel violence" of the ceasefire. Israel will act "with determination" to bring it home, warned, denouncing "the cruelty of Hamas monsters" that "will pay" for it. "The entire civil world should condemn these horrible murders," Netanyahu added, ensuring that he will not have "peace until the savages who executed our hostages will not be insured for justice."
Hamas dismissed the violation of the truce, claiming that the exchange of the remains was "an error" when the bodies were extracted from the rubble after the Israeli bombing that killed the Bibas in November 2023. The Palestinian militant group called for the return of the psalm of the Gaza woman delivered yesterday, while ensuring that it intends to continue with the implementation of the agreement for the ceasefire in the Strip and the release of hostages. Tomorrow six more abducts will be released, in exchange for 602 Palestinian prisoners, including 60 who are serving long sentences and 50 ergastolani.
&nbsp;
Hamas will free Tal Shoham, Omer Shem-Tov, Eliya Cohen, Omer Wenkert, Avera Mengistu and Hisham al-Sayed. The last two have been held in the Strip for a decade after entering two different circumstances by mistake, the other four were taken hostage on 7 October 2023. These are the last live hostages that will be returned at the first stage of the agreement. As for the next phase, the talks have not yet been started and yesterday the Palestinian group accused Netanyahu of "tergiversare", among the fears of the relatives of the hostages still prisoners who risk remaining in the Strip if the agreement collapses.
&nbsp;
Meanwhile, the leaders of the six countries of the Gulf Cooperation Council, together with Egypt and Jordan, are gathered to discuss an alternative plan for Gaza to the one proposed by US President Donald Trump, which provides for the forced displacement of Palestinians. The meeting "non-official brother", as defined by the Saudi state press agency, takes place in view of the urgent meeting of the Arab League set for March 4 in Cairo. Egypt is working on a project for the reconstruction of the Strip which has not yet provided details, but according to the former Egyptian diplomat Mohamed Hegazy will be crafted "in three technical phases over a period between three and five years."
The first phase, lasting six months, will focus on the "fast recovery" and the removal of debris, will be followed by an international conference on reconstruction, in particular public infrastructure, while in the final phase there will be urban planning, reconstruction of housing buildings, provision of services and the establishment of a "political path to implement the solution of the two states". &nbsp;
